<TITLE> IMF praises Burundi on 2 pct inflation, raps graft </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BUJUMBURA, Aug 8 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The International Monetary Fund praised Burundi on Wednesday for its exceptionally low inflation rate of just 2 percent for the past year to August. But the fund said it remained worried about reports of graft in the tiny, war-torn central African country, where police this month arrested the central bank governor in connection with a multi-million dollar corruption scandal. "Inflation over the last twelve months in this country has been 2 percent. Very few countries in the World have achieved this," IMF country director Enrique De La Piedra told journalists. Western economic powerhouses such as the United States, Britain and the European Union often struggle to meet their 2 percent inflation targets. "We are happy that the government has shown a commitment to keep inflation (low)," De La Piedra said But he urged Burundian authorities to deal with cases of alleged embezzlement, referring to the arrest this month of central bank governor Isaac Bizimana for alleged unauthorised payments totalling $21 million to oil importer Interpetrol. "The IMF cannot remain indifferent before cases of embezzlement and we want the government to explain how it will recover all the money it lost in this overpayment", he said. The fund has projected Burundi's economic growth at less than 5 percent this year, owing to falling coffee output. The government expects this year's coffee production to fall to around 10,000 tonnes from 31,000 the previous year, largely because of ageing coffee tre
